# Success Forged in Resilience
The technology industry has for a long time been presumed to be a male dominated field, however history tells a different story. Women have been in technology playing critical roles in shaping the digital landscape. The women may not match the number of men in this industry but have pioneered both early computing, automations and modern advancements. They have made ground breaking contributions to the industry despite the different systemic challenges they have faced and continue to face. This blog highlights some of these remarkable women and the works they did.

## Ada Lovelace – The First Computer Programmer
Born in 1815 in the now London, Lovelace was raised by a single mother after her parents legally separated. She was educated privately by tutors and she also self-educated. At the age of 12 Ada wanted to build a flying machine but abandoned it midway because she did not have the capacity at the time. She was still very much in love with machine and there after an introduction to Babbages, She developed interest in Charles Babbages works and worked with him on the analytical machine where she did the annotations. The analytical machine was regarded as a mechanical general purpose computer. Lovelace played a critical role in the building of this machine by writing the first algorithm for a machine which demonstrated that computers had the capability of doing more than just calculations. 
Ada faced so many challenges on her journey to becoming the pioneer of the modern computer science. During that time, women were only considered mothers and wives and nothing more could come from them apart from that. But Ada forged her way through private tutors, self education, innovation, creativity. It is worth noting that her work was never recognized until the early 20th century when people saw the significance of some of the algorithms she wrote.

One would argue that if Ada had not written the first computer programme someone else would have done it. However, that would be simplifying what she did and failing to applaud the good work she did despite the systemic challenges she faced. 

## Grace Hopper – The Mother of Computer Programming
Grace a computer pioneer and a naval officer with a masters degree and Ph.D in mathematics from Yale. Born in 1906 in New York, Grace is widely known for a her contributions in computer programming, software development and the design and implementation of programmming languages.
Grace the United States army during world war two after initially being rejected because of her age. She persisted and finally got in and had the opportunity of serving her country in the naval reserve. After completing her training she was assigned to the Bureau of ships computation project where she worked with a team on IBM automation sequence controlled calculator also known as the MARK I, which was the first electromechanical computer. 
She further developed the first compiler, a tool that translates human-readable code into machine language. She was instrumental in creating COBOL, one of the first programming languages. During her time, women in both the military and technology fields faced immense prejudice and people doubted their capability to deliver on tasks compared to their male counterparts. Hopper had to overcome gender bias in a predominantly male military and computing world, where women were rarely seen as innovators. Her persistence and expertise allowed her to break through these barriers, proving her technical prowess and earning a lasting legacy.

## Conclusion  
There are so many women in the tech field today thanks to different programs that aim to encourage the tech courses uptake right from University. However it is important to recognize and acknowledge the women we forged success through resilience in the face of challenges.

Today the biggest challenge is that women down play their work and shy off from showing off their work. A little push would go along way in encouraging such women to come the light. Remember only a positive push can do good.
